Task 1

Part a)

To understand if bookmakers are good at predicting the outcomes of over/under bets, the probability of a score over 2.5 in any game (an over situation) was calculated two different ways. The first way used the reciprocal of the bookmakers odds, and was termed the Odds Probability. This defined the bookmakers expectation, and was normalized from odds data by extracting the margin. In the second way, the ratio of matches which actually ended over among a certain group of matches with similar Odds Probabilities was determined. This was termed the Empirical Probability and represented the real probability of the match ending over. To aggregate data for a sensible visualization, the matches were binned based on the Odds Probabilities associated with them. At least 30 matches were required per bin in each bookmakers case so as to get a statistically meaningful result.

We make extensive use of the data.table package to chain together operations:

# modify odd_details to get the first and last over/under
# bets, find Odd Probabilities and bin upper bounds
odd_details_ou_latest_over <- copy(odd_details_ou)[islatest == 
    TRUE][, `:=`(c("islatest", "isearliest"), NULL)][, `:=`(impprob, 
    oneoverodd/sum(oneoverodd)), by = list(matchId, bookmaker)][oddtype == 
    "over"][, `:=`(bintop, ceiling(impprob/0.05) * 0.05)]
odd_details_ou_earliest_over <- copy(odd_details_ou)[isearliest == 
    TRUE][, `:=`(c("islatest", "isearliest"), NULL)][, `:=`(impprob, 
    oneoverodd/sum(oneoverodd)), by = list(matchId, bookmaker)][oddtype == 
    "over"][, `:=`(bintop, ceiling(impprob/0.05) * 0.05)]

matches_ou <- copy(matches)[, `:=`(c("date", "leagueId", "type"), 
    NULL)][, `:=`(isover, homescore + awayscore > handicaplvl)]

# modify matches to find Empirical Probabilities, this has to
# be done where each match is a unique entry to avoid more
# betted-on matches skewing average
matches_ou_bins_latest <- unique(merge(matches_ou, odd_details_ou_latest_over[, 
    c("matchId", "bintop")], by = "matchId"))[, `:=`(emp, mean(isover)), 
    by = bintop]
matches_ou_bins_earliest <- unique(merge(matches_ou, odd_details_ou_earliest_over[, 
    c("matchId", "bintop")], by = "matchId"))[, `:=`(emp, mean(isover)), 
    by = bintop]

    2), pch = c(1, 2))

There are three takeaways from this analysis. The first is that unsurprisingly, the bookmakers tend to predict the empirical probabiliries fairly accurately. The second is that the initial and final odds seem to be fairly close. The third is that the distribution seems to follow a logistic-like curve, where bookmakers will overestimate the probability of an over when an over is very unlikely and underestimate the probability of an over when it is very likely.

Part b)

For this part, the performance of bookmaker 10Bet was considered over the years since 2010. To this end, the data was assigned more granular probability values - both for the odd-based and empirical cases - by doing the same analysis explained above for each year. Instead of drawing separate plots for the Odds Probability and the Empirical Probability, the absolute value of their difference was taken for each year, giving rise to a plot which measures how off 10Bets odds-based predictions have been over the years. Different line plots were drawn for each bin.

The analysis shows that 10Bet, over the years, has mostly been successful at keeping errors below 10%, especially predicting the 0.60-0.70 Odds probability region with really low errors in the past few years (corresponding to odds ~1.4-1.7). However, there is a curious period - in 2012 and 2013, when 10Bet averaged nearly 35% error from the Empirical Probabilities.

Task 2

A quick visualization of whether the change in the odds can give us any predictive information can be done by making a histogram. To this end 1x2 odd data, which is for betting on whether the home or away team wins (or there is a draw) was used. I wanted to see whether a home team victory could be predicted by a large (downward) change in the home team victory odd 1. For the 10Bet bookmaker, the data was filtered to keep only final and initial odd values and their difference. Histograms were plotted given home victory and not-home-victory.

Unfortunately this visualization is not very helpful - it shows that given a home victory, the variance of the odd difference is lower, but the odds tend to stay the same more than they change.
